06261nam a22007215i 9781847421821DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20092009xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847421821  a(DE-B1597)646484  a(OCoLC)472871130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 7aPOL0280002bisacsh04a35104aThe consumer in public services :bChoice, values and difference /ced. by Richard Simmons, Martin Powell, Ian Greener. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tList of figures and tables -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on contributors -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: managing the ‘unmanageable consumer’ -- tThe consumer and New Labour: the consumer as king? -- tNarratives of public service delivery in the UK: comparing central and local government -- tUnderstanding the ‘differentiated consumer’ in public services -- tDifferentiating consumers in professional services: information empowerment and the emergence of the fragmented consumer -- tThe healthcare consumer -- tThe consumer in education -- tThe consumer and social housing -- tThe people’s police? Citizens, consumers and communities -- tThe consumer in social care -- tDifferentiated consumers? A differentiated view from a service user perspective -- tAuthoritative consumers or experts by experience? User groups in health and social care -- tThe public service consumer as member -- tConclusion: the consumer in public services -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book challenges existing stereotypes about the 'consumer as chooser'. It shows how we must develop a more sophisticated understanding of consumers, examining their place and role as users of public services. The analysis shows that there are many different 'faces' of the consumer and that it is not easy to categorise users in particular environments. Drawing on empirical research, The consumer in public services critiques established assumptions surrounding citizenship and consumption. Choice may grab the policy headlines but other essential values are revealed as important throughout the book. One issue concerns the 'subjects' of consumerism, or who it is that presents themselves when they come to use public services. Another concerns consumer 'mechanisms', or the ways that public services try to relate to these people. Bringing these issues together for the first time, with cutting-edge contributions from a range of leading researchers, the message is that today's public services must learn to cope with a differentiated public. This book will be of interest to scholars and students in the fields of social policy and public administration. It will also appeal to policy-makers leading 'user-focused' public service reforms, as well as those responsible for implementing such reforms at the frontline of modern public services.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aPublic administrationzGreat BritainxPublic services. 0aPublic utilitiesxCustomer serviceszGreat Britain. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBarnes, Marian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeresford, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirchall, Johnston, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoheny, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarrell, Catherine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlendinning, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r